      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<p><hr /></p><p><span id=\"htZoomImageMsg\"></span></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nIn life, we are always searching for explanations for the events around us. Some of these explanations, although they use words that may seem correct at first glance, do not hold up when tested in experiments. On the other hand, there are explanations that prove strong, and every time we test them again, we are able to confirm them. But, after all, how can we tell if an explanation is truly good?",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_propose",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### The Proposal of a Method\n\nThe use of an investigative method occurred at distinct moments and in different locations. In this text, we will study the work of Ibn Al-Haytham and Sir Francis Bacon.\n\n#### Ibn Al-Haytham\n\nWhen we study the work of Ibn Al-Haytham, we observe a precise description of his experiments, which led him to conclude that we see something because light hits an object and reflects into our eyes (<htcite0>; <htcite1>; <htcite2>).\n\nScientific experiments, like those of Ibn Al-Haytham, help us confirm the models we create to explain nature: it is useless to simply say that something works in a certain way if we cannot verify that explanation through measurements.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "8cca37d0-35bb-42ae-8700-f425c98f4f28",
                     "text": "Sabra, A. I.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1989",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e1ddee69-8fc6-4e27-8160-c4077916aed9",
                     "text": "Tbakhi, Abdelghani, and Samir S. Amr.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2007",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ed3bf544-1c30-4109-9521-f68fa8eff0e7",
                     "text": "Al-Khalili, J.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2015",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"Experiment\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('Experiment', '0%')\" src=\"images/Archive/The_Optics_of_Ibn_al-Haytham_22.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: Description of the experiments by Ibn Al-Haytham. Image extracted from Archive (<htcite0>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "de651eda-c584-444f-9ec0-67f1a43aa4a6",
                     "text": "The Optics Of Ibn Al Haytham, Books I III, On Direct Vision",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Sir Francis Bacon\n\nWhen Sir Francis Bacon published the *Novum Organum*, he defined the method known as the Baconian method. This method outlines scientific investigations in specific steps",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 0,
                     "uuid": "051faac0-97a3-4ff3-83f7-346c8a7dd14d",
                     "text": "Lord Bacon",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1902",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a8eff431-07fc-4e9f-8654-5d144783218c",
                     "text": "Britannica, T. Editors of Encyclopaedia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "- Description of observed facts.\n- Tabulation or classification of these facts.\n- Evaluation and acceptance or rejection of elements associated with observed phenomena based on these classifications.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### United Contribution\n\nBoth works contributed to the development of science as we know it, helping us explain and understand the nature. These contributions have enabled important advances in our lives, such as the treatment of diseases.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_using_method",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Using the Method\n\nLet’s conduct a brief experiment to test the the method. Before proceeding, take a moment to reflect:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: On Sounds</b><br /><br />Do different objects produce the same sound when shaken inside a box?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "To answer this question, we will use a box, like the one represented in Chart 1:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><svg width=\"300\" height=\"300\" viewBox=\"-25 -25 50 50\"><line x1=\"5\" y1=\"20\" x2=\"20\" y2=\"5\" style=\"stroke:#000;\"/> <line x1=\"-20\" y1=\"-5\" x2=\"-5\" y2=\"-20\" style=\"stroke:#000;\"/> <line x1=\"5\" y1=\"-5\" x2=\"20\" y2=\"-20\" style=\"stroke:#000;\"/> <line x1=\"-20\" y1=\"20\" x2=\"5\" y2=\"20\" style=\"stroke:#000;\"/> <line x1=\"-20\" y1=\"-5\" x2=\"5\" y2=\"-5\" style=\"stroke:#000;\"/>  <line x1=\"-5\" y1=\"-20\" x2=\"20\" y2=\"-20\" style=\"stroke:#000;\"/>  <line x1=\"-20\" y1=\"20\" x2=\"-20\" y2=\"-5\" style=\"stroke:#000;\"/>   <line x1=\"5\" y1=\"20\" x2=\"5\" y2=\"-5\" style=\"stroke:#000;\"/> <line x1=\"20\" y1=\"5\" x2=\"20\" y2=\"-20\" style=\"stroke:#000;\"/> <line x1=\"-20\" y1=\"20\" x2=\"-5\" y2=\"5\" style=\"stroke:#000;stroke-dasharray:1,1;\"/> <line x1=\"-5\" y1=\"5\" x2=\"20\" y2=\"5\" style=\"stroke:#000;stroke-dasharray:1,1;\"/> <line x1=\"-5\" y1=\"5\" x2=\"-5\" y2=\"-20\" style=\"stroke:#000;stroke-dasharray:1,1;\"/> </svg></center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 1</b>: Box used in the following examples.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_lab_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_lab question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-microscope\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_lab\"><b>Practice 1: Testing Noise</b><br /><br />Obtain a small box made of a material that produces noise when shaken.<br /><br />Choose three small objects that are smaller than the box itself, such as a bean, a small rock, and a piece of cotton.<br /><br />Take a sheet of paper and write down the name of each object, along with the anticipated sound it will produce. Assign a number between 1 and 3 to indicate the expected sound level relative to the other objects. For example:<br /><b>Cotton: faint noise - 1</b><br /><b>Bean: moderate noise – 2</b><br /><b>Rock: loud noise – 3</b><br /><br />Place one object inside the box at a time, close it, and shake it. Compare the actual sound produced with your initial predictions.<br /><br />If the observed results align with your predictions, your hypothesis is confirmed. Any discrepancies indicate a need to reassess your initial assumptions. If the results are drastically different, the hypothesis may need to be discarded.</div></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Initial observations may suggest that larger objects produce louder sounds than smaller ones. However, this experiment represents only the beginning of scientific inquiry. Let’s proceed to a second experiment:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_lab_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_lab question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-microscope\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_lab\"><b>Practice 2: Confirming Results</b><br />Now, obtain three different objects from those in the first experiment, such as a grain of rice, granulated sugar, and a small piece of crumpled paper.<br /><br />Create an ordered list similar to the one used in the first experiment.<br /><br />Repeat the process of placing one object inside the box at a time, shaking it, and comparing the observed sound with your hypothesis.</div></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The process outlined in these practices mirrors the methodology employed by scientists when investigating natural phenomena. Upon concluding their research, scientists typically submit their findings to academic journals, where peer reviewers assess the validity of their work through replication attempts. If successful, the paper is published, contributing to the collective pool of scientific knowledge.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_update",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Progress of Science\n\n#### A New Discovery\n\nImagine that today, a new discovery contradicts an idea that had persisted for centuries. Now, consider this:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: On Discoveries</b><br /><br />What happens to previous understanding? Was the prior knowledge wrong? Or is there more to consider?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "We must approach terms like \"correct\" and \"wrong\" with caution (<htcite0>; <htcite1>; <htcite2>). New research may reveal limitations in prior findings without invalidating them completely.\n\nFor example, we shouldn't discard Newton's law of gravitation in favor of Einstein's theory of relativity. While Newton's model can't explain all cosmic phenomena, it remains valid for most Earth-based observations (<htcite3>; <htcite4>; <htcite5>; <htcite6>; <htcite7>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b6f9bd52-c0cb-497e-9217-1f9677d5b491",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
